Yes, saying "skew dispersion trading" makes sense, as it refers to a sophisticated, specialized strategy within equity volatility trading that combines elements of both, although it is more frequently referred to as part of volatility relative value trading or dispersion trading with skew considerations. 

Here is a breakdown of why this term is valid and how it functions:
    1. Defining the Components
        Dispersion Trading: A market-neutral strategy that profits from the difference between the implied volatility (IV) of an index (like the S&P 500) and the realized volatility of its component stocks. Traders usually sell index options (high IV) and buy individual stock options (lower IV), betting that stocks will move more independently than the index anticipates.
        Volatility Skew (or Smile): Refers to the phenomenon where implied volatility differs across different strike prices for options on the same underlying asset. Typically, out-of-the-money (OTM) puts have higher IV than ATM options, indicating fear of a crash (negative skew). 

    2. Why "Skew Dispersion" Makes Sense
    Dispersion is not just a bet on correlation, but also a bet on the shape of volatility surfaces (skew). 
        Disparity in Skew: Index options often exhibit a much more pronounced, steep put skew than single-stock options. A dispersion trader is often taking a view on this skew difference—selling the expensive index skew and buying cheaper, flatter individual stock skews.
        "Dirty" Dispersion: In reality, single-stock options have unique skew patterns (due to dividends, borrow rates, etc.) that do not perfectly match the index, making the trade "dirty". Traders must manage these skewed distributions across hundreds of names.
        Skew Adjustments: When dispersion traders select stocks, they are looking for specific, non-parallel skew structures. 

    3. How the Trade Works
    When a trader puts on a "skew dispersion" trade, they are betting that:
        Correlation will fall: The stocks will move independently, allowing the long stock volatility to pay off.
        Relative skew will revert: The overpriced skew in the index will narrow relative to the underpriced skew of individual stocks. 

In summary, referring to it as "skew dispersion" emphasizes that the trader is not just trading volatility levels, but is actively exploiting the differences in the implied skew structure between the index and its components. 
